TY  - JOUR
AU  - Jacob, Martin
AU  - Michaely, Roni
T1  - Taxation and Dividend Policy: The Muting Effect of Agency Issues and Shareholder Conflicts
PY  - 2017
Y1  - 2017/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhx041
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 30
IS  - 9
SP  - 3176
EP  - 3222
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Using proprietary data on the entire spectrum of ownership structure and exact tax status of investors and firms, we examine how dividend taxation affects payout. Utilizing an exogenous shock to dividend taxation, we show that absent any frictions, dividend taxation has a large impact on payout. As agency issues and shareholder conflicts increase, owners’ tax preferences have significantly smaller impact on payout. Three mechanisms reduce the dividend-tax sensitivity: Coordination among owners, heterogeneity in tax preferences, and diverging objectives between managers and owners. Altogether, taxation has a first-order impact on payout, but agency issues and shareholder conflicts mute its impact substantially.Received June 20, 2016; editorial decision January 24, 2017 by Editor Francesca Cornelli.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhx041
ER  - 



